webpackJsonp([1081],{"./node_modules/json-loader/index.js!./.cache/json/articles-linux-some-usages-for-linux.json":function(e,r){e.exports={data:{markdownRemark:{html:'<ul>\n<li>Linux now operates on the majority of smartphones and tablets around the world via the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Android_(operating_system)">Android</a> OS (based off the Linux kernel). As of March 2016 Android holds <a href="https://www.netmarketshare.com/operating-system-market-share.aspx?qprid=8&#x26;qpcustomd=1">60.99%</a> of the market share on mobile devices (tablets and smartphones). It also holds <a href="http://www.idc.com/prodserv/smartphone-os-market-share.jsp">82.8%</a> for smartphones alone (per 2015 Q2 numbers).</li>\n<li>As of March 2016, Alexa reported that <a href="http://www.w3cook.com/os/summary/">96.55%</a> of the top 1 million Internet domains in the world are powered by servers running Linux.</li>\n<li>The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_Stock_Exchange">New York Stock Exchange (NYSE)</a>, the largest stock exchange in the world which trades securities worth billions of dollars daily are executed by servers that run on Linux after moving away from UNIX.</li>\n<li>The White House powers their web servers using <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Hat">Red Hat Linux</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_HTTP_Server">Apache</a>.</li>\n<li>The US Department of Defense (DoD) uses Linux to run their nuclear submarine fleet.</li>\n<li>The US Navy uses Linux for ground control software.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Other adoptions of Linux from around the world can be viewed <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Linux_adopters">here</a> and <a href="http://www.comparebusinessproducts.com/fyi/50-places-linux-running-you-might-not-expect">here</a></p>',frontmatter:{title:"Some Usages for Linux",parent:"/home/stuart/guides/src/pages/articles/linux/some-usages-for-linux/index.md absPath of file"}}},pathContext:{slug:"/articles/linux/some-usages-for-linux/"}}}});
